When I computed value by dividing capacity by the cost per battery of the cheapest package size, they took a respectable third place, and they have the advantage of being a trusted name compared to the value leader. In the images I have attached a graph and a table summarizing my test results for the 7 types I've tested, but if you'd like to know more about how I test ... on to the in-dept test & review.I've been on a bit of a quest to test all of the top-selling aaa batteries on Amazon in a repeatable, precise way. This means the same equipment, same environmental conditions, and same slots in the equipment will be used for each test. For each test, I fully discharge 3 batteries in my Opus BT-C2000 battery analyzer at rates of 100 ma, 200 ma, and 400 ma (discharge rate affects usable capacity). I have also performed this exact same test (same equipment, same conditions) on the ACDelco, Duracell Procell, Duracell Coppertop, Energizer MAX, Maxell, and Rayovac. I have linked the other brands I've reviewed at the end of this review if you'd like to take a look at the other results for comparison purposes. For the Amazon Basics batteries, the capacity at each discharge rate was:Disch Rt | Capacity | Runtime | Sample use case100 mA | 997 mAh | 10 hrs | Low-power LED flashlight200 mA | 914 mAh | 4.5 hrs | Electronic toy / medium LED flashlight400 mA | 623 mAh | 1.5 hrs | Motorized toy / bright LED flashlightNote that these (and all other Alkalines) would achieve somewhat higher capacity (maybe 1200 mAh) in a low discharge application like a mouse, keyboard, remote control, etc because alkaline batteries have internal resistance that reduces usable capacity at high discharge rates.The capacity of these batteries is among the best I've tested -- take a look at the attached data table for comparative data. For the cost (~$0.31/ea in a 36 pack right now), these are a decent but beatable value -- the power supplied per dollar spent is very good, but eclipsed by other currently available options.Comparison:These batteries do well capacity-wise, but value-wise are blown away by the currently cheapest energy/dollar battery that I've tested, the ACDelco aaa's. Their capacity results were:Disch Rt | Capacity | Runtime100 mA | 1005 mAh | 10 hrs200 mA | 864 mAh | 4.3 hrs400 mA | 670 mAh | 1.7 hrsAs you can see, the Amazon batteries were very comperable ... but, at the current time the AmazonBasics batteries are $0.31/ea (36 pack), while the ACDelco batteries are about $0.21/ea (48 pack) -- so the ACDelco are significantly cheaper per mAh. I did not test shelf life, so it's possible that these may hold up better sitting in a drawer. Although both the Amazon batteries and the ACDelco batteries are certainly made on contract by a third party, I do think that I trust Amazon a bit more to provide consistent batteries than ACDelco ... although I haven't had any trouble with my ACDelco batteries so far. It's also worth noting that the Amazon batteries come in clearly superior packaging - while the ACDelco batteries come in a horrible gigantic plastic blister pack, the Amazon batteries come in a closable cardboard box. If you don't go through a lot of batteries & organization of your battery drawer is important to you, that could push them into the all-around winner category despite the ~50% price premium.Finally, because another review specifically mentions the Rayovac AA's as being 'good' in some usage scenarios, I thought I'd share my findings for the Rayovac AAA's. In short, they're garbage - the Amazon batteries are better in EVERY case. It's possible that the Rayovac AA's are much better than the AAA's, but I think it's more likely that the version of the Rayovacs tested by the website that he got his results from is different than the most popular Rayovac on Amazon (I source all of my batteries from Amazon). I ran the Rayovac test several times because I couldn't believe how poorly they did ... here are some typical Rayovac results:Disch Rt | Capacity | Runtime100 mA | 908 mAh | 9 hrs200 mA | 590 mAh | 2.9 hrs400 mA | 443 mAh | 1.1 hrsMy other battery tests/reviews:I have posted reviews for Duracell Coppertop, Duracell Procell and ACDelco aaa alkaline batteries with capacity data gathered using the exact same method and equipment. Best value I've had on batteries.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 25, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "5.0 out of 5 stars DuraCell and EverReady Don't Hold a Candle to This Work Horse", 'author': 'Born in Kansas', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I am now a strongly committed believer in this brand that outperforms by wide margins, over the 2 brands which deliver the most hype through advertising. I have always been a DuraCell customer and decided to purchase in quantity, for all of the devices I have at home. And I do a lot of traveling which requires the use of AAA batteries in mobile devices (outside of typical smartphones, etc).I stumbled upon a review for ACDelco batteries, which was done by a consumer who had battery discharge test equipment to measure the actual load and capacity of multiple brands of batteries, ignoring all of the advertising hype, which motivates people to buy one over another, This reviewer. tested all of the major brands, taking brand new batteries of each and putting them through a regimen of uses to see how quickly they drained, under various loads. He had a battery discharge measuring device (Opus), which draws specific levels of power, from light to heavy loads, and yields the results in a measurable way. I love it when someone posts a review which peels back the skin of an onion, to see what is really going on "under the hood". In case you can\'t find his review, I am quoting it in parentheses below, after my comments.At first, I was a bit bit surprised, being a long time "victim" of DuraCell and EverReady advertising, having never considered ACDelco, but then it made a lot of sense that this General Motors company and brand has always equipped their new cars with their own ACDelco batteries. It certainly makes sense that they might have a deeper brain trust of technology to deliver a superior "small electronics" battery. At any rate, I am extremely pleased that I stumbled upon his review, which means a lot more to me than all of the advertising hype, which does nothing to deliver any actual credible and unbiased information.The reviewer goes by the profile name of just "C" and is an Amazon Top 1000 Reviewer. His review is at the top of reviews for the ACDelco battery page on Amazon with the following linkhttps://www.amazon.com/ACDelco-Batteries-Alkaline-Battery-Performance/dp/B00FF8KQJC/ref=pd_sim_121_4?_encoding=UTF8&refRID=WYRQGK7Z5SQ285XRJ6SS&th=1Below is his review without the images which he attached, showing his test equipment and charts of his results for 6 Brands tested.C (TOP 1000 REVIEWER)5.0 out of 5 stars6 Brands Tested: Capacity test results + a clear winnerOctober 31, 2015I couldn\'t find a review stating the tested capacity of the leading AAA batteries on Amazon, so I took it upon myself to find out. For each of the 6 types I\'ve tested (ACDelco, AmazonBasics, Duracell Coppertop, Duracell Procell, Energizer, and Rayovac), I discharged 3 batteries in my Opus BT-C2000 battery analyzer at rates of 100 ma, 200 ma, and 400 ma (discharge rate affects usable capacity). These ACDelco batteries were among the top in capacity, and stomped EVERY other battery in terms of value, with AmazonBasics as a runner-up.The capacity at each discharge rate was:Disch Rt | Capacity | Runtime | Sample use case100 mA | 1005 mAh | 10.1 hrs | Low-power LED flashlight200 mA | 864 mAh | 4.3 hrs | Electronic toy / medium LED flashlight400 mA | 670 mAh | 1.7 hrs | Motorized toy / bright LED flashlightI ran the ACDelco batteries first, and my original review I stated that "Though not top-notch, these results are perfectly respectable". Well, since then I\'ve run 5 more brands, and these are pretty close to top-notch. The only other brand that managed to beat them in ANY category was AmazonBasics, but really AmazonBasics and ACDelco were at the top of the stack and the differences were probably within the margin of error. Put simply: these batteries pack a lot of punch, and they\'re cheap. For the cost (~$10 as of this writing), these are an excellent value -- the power supplied per dollar spent is nearly unbeatable for a non-rechargeable aaa battery, AND the capacity is very nearly the best I\'ve tested.I have not tested shelf life or leak resistance for any of the batteries in my roundup, so it\'s possible that some of the other batteries may do better in that regard. The one thing I *have* learned is that a battery\'s marketing has nothing to do with its actual performance for power capacity ... assuming that the same is true for storage, you\'ll have to wait until somebody runs a thorough leak and storage test to know which brand is best.I have posted reviews for Duracell Procell, Duracell Coppertop, Energizer, and AmazonBasics aaa alkaline batteries with capacity data gathered using the exact same method and equipment. I have attached a graph and table summarizing the results in the images. To find the full reviews for the other brands for comparison purposes, go to the product pages linked below and search for \'mah\' under \'all reviews\' (or just browse to them on my profile)."" End Quote', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States November 8, 2017', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Great value!', 'author': 'Mamaenthusiast', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'Great value but definitely do not last as long as Duracell. Those devices for me are blood pressure devices, and a medical device remote control. When I use a multimeter to test the voltages instead of a basic battery good/bad tester, I find that Duracell brand unused batteries test at 1.58 volts where these EBL test less than 1.5 volts. Batteries always lose voltage as they are used, and some devices need more volts than others. I recommend that you buy small quantity of the battery you need and test with your specific device/s, and keep in mind that some devices will work longer with a more expensive name brand like Duracell and Energizer. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Power Up!', 'author': 'SuperTed', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Since I have a couple of remote controls, console controllers and many other things around the house that go thru AA batteries quite a bit, I picked up these PowerFlash AA Batteries to feed that demand.The batteries are, well, like any other batteries you see from any other manufacturer. You get 16 of these at a great price. I pulled a couple out just to test with my battery meter and I\'m happy to report that they all reported as "Good" (1.5v) on the meter. I wasn\'t really expecting them NOT to, but it\'s always good to be sure.AA batteries are so ubiquitous that there really is no need to buy top of the line name brands at 3 to 4 times the cost unless you have a device you heavily rely on. Even then, is it really worth the cost? In my experience, off brand battery brands have lasted just as long as the name brands, so I have the utmost confidence these ones from PowerFlash will provide me with the same results.Anyways, I did pop several of these in my remotes and so far, so good. Every one came up as 1.64vDC on both HP and Realtek digital voltmeters. So they look good out of the box, and 1.64vDC is up there with the name brands. That's the good news.Beyond that, this doesn't tell me for sure how long they will last in real use. And testing that takes some time, and setting up a couple of test environments for different drain usages. Instead, I will report back if it appears these are repeatedly coming under expectations for lifetime. Meanwhile, nothing indicates they are duds by any stretch. Again, so far, good news.But here's where things aren't so good. While you can easily spend $0.67/each for top brand AA batteries here on Amazon or you can do these at $0.50 each, there are more than a few others offering AAs that aren't top tier at $0.50 each, but aren't mystery brands, either. That price is 2/3rds the big labels, but some of the other second tier names offer this lower price, too, while I'd call this brand an unknown.Is it a good price? Is it a potential money saver? Possibly Is it a best deal? Not so sure. If I can get the same price on some already established discount brands, I can't see the motivation to go with these over those others with a discount but known name.Maybe these are equal in actual use. Maybe somehow better. But also maybe not either of those. Until that's clear, I'd be more motivated if they ware more like $0.35/each or less. But at $0.50, probably not a repeat customer, at least not for now. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars One Size Replaces Many', 'author': 'Craig Clausen', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I was a bit confused about the size. The description said, "Package includes: 10PCS AG13 L1154f LR44 Button Cell Batteries." I thought that meant it was a variety pack containing some of each AG13, L1154d, and LR44, but they\'re all LR44, and apparently that size can also replace several others. The battery from the pictured clock had been removed long ago, and I had no idea what size was in there, but one of these little buttons worked. It\'s only been a few days since I put it in. Hopefully I won\'t know how long it lasts for quite some time. Another once of these powered up a different desk clock that had also been missing a battery for years.I don\'t have any fancy equipment to tell you what their charge was upon arrival, but the package (pictured) states best by 12/2028, so just under 4 years from my order. I originally thought that was minimal, but upon reviewing the description, they only promise 3-year shelf life, so I guess they over-delivered.I loved that I was able to get these out of the packaging with ease. I\'ve had other button cell batteries so tightly sealed in plastic that they practically had to be melted out of their case, but these have perforated slots in the cardboard back making them easy to remove.I do think it\'s a bit sketchy that they use the Duracell colors considering these are obviously not Duracells, but I guess if Duracell doesn\'t have the color scheme trademarked, it\'s Juninxiu\'s prerogative.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 27, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for Bore Sights', 'author': 'SuperTed', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I have a 12 gauge laser bore sight that takes LR44 batteries and I picked these up to use as backups as you can never have too many in my opinion.Not much to say here other than you get a pack of 10. I immediately popped one of them into my battery tester and it showed up at 1.56v so that checks out. The bore sight I have takes THREE of these, so I loaded it up with three and it worked (see pics). That's all I can ask for.Anyone who uses bore sights knows that the laser draws a lot of energy so typically these don't last long if you have it constantly on during the zeroing of your red dot sight, hence why you need a goodly amount of backups. Also, anyone who has read my previous reviews on batteries knows that I typically use generic/no-name brands over name brand anyways and I almost never have longevity issues with them. Batteries are so ubiquitous that you don't need to spend 2-3 times the cost. These ones from JUNINXIU work just fine.I'm satisfied.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 25, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect fit for my pachymeter', 'author': 'Izzy', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I have a pachymeter that, unfortunately, after some time not using it, drains the battery. The 1.5V Energizer Max is rated for 10 years of shelf life, which is double what these Coast batteries are rated for. The per battery price on a 24-pack of Energizer Max is also cheaper than the Coast. It'd be hard to say whether the anti-leak design really works, but I haven't had any leaking problems with the Energizers (knock on wood). The worst for corrosion and leaking in my experience are Duracells. i also stopped buying the junkie Kirkland batteries at Costco. I no longer use alkaline batteries in my flashlights after a pair of Duracells ruined a very expensive, LED Lenser flashlight that I loved. I use low-discharge rechargeable batteries in my flashlights, with alkalines as my backups. Once I'm done, I remove the alkalines batteries. The Coast 4-pack comes in a nice little cardboard package that's easy to throw in my backpack and forget until I need them. The Energizer Max AA 24-packs also come in similar packaging, FYI.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 5, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '1.0 out of 5 stars Ridiculously Overpriced Commodity Batteries', 'author': 'Terry S', 'rating': 1, 'content': 'I hate to use non-rechargeable AA batteries because of their associated waste, but there’s often no practical way to avoid them. The USB-rechargeable lithium-ion batteries that recently came on the market are great, but they’re expensive. I’m not about to buy enough of them to replace ALL of the AA batteries that I need for household use. So every few years I pick up a big pack of Energizers at Sam’s or Wal-Mart, and they last me for quite a while.The price of a 48-pack of AAs at Sam’s as I write this is $0.49 per battery; it’s a little more at Wal-Mart and maybe a little more still at other places. But nowhere did I see a price as high as $0.98 per battery, which, currently at $3.90 for a four-pack, is what these Coast AA Industrial Performance Alkaline Batteries cost.There’s nothing special about these batteries, and certainly nothing to justify them costing twice as much as other brands. Their specifications are the same, their construction is the same, their chemistry is the same and their five-year storage life is unimpressive; I’ve bought AA batteries dated 10 years out, so a five-year life gets a big yawn from me.I don’t often rate Vine items with one star, and if my rating were only based on performance, I’d give these batteries three stars; as a commodified product, they’re as good as, but no better or worse than, other brands. They work as intended, and there’s nothing else to say about that. But at almost a buck apiece? That’s obscene, in my opinion. L1154f Battery AG13 L1154 LR44 SR44 A76 Button L1154h Button Batteries Alkaline Coin Cell (30 Count)
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars JUNINXIU L1154f Battery AG13 L1154 LR44 SR44 A76 Button Batteries Alkaline Coin Cell (30 Count)', 'author': 'A.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'These batteries come inside a black ziplock bag. Each of the three 10-packs is in retail-style packaging, with a hole for hanging on a peg. (However, they only have Amazon inventory barcodes, not a retail-style UPC.) An expiration date is printed on the back of each pack. The ones I received in March 2024 say they are "best before" Dec 2028 - nearly 5 years. The pack also says they are made with mercury-free chemistry.In use, they might not last quite as long as the Energizer or Duracell equivalents, but currently you can get 30 of these batteries (three 10-packs) for about the same cost as a single 3-pack of the major brands. I have several devices that require this LR44/AG13/357 button battery size, so it\'s great to have some more affordable spare batteries for them.And another point in favor of these off-brand batteries, for me... In the last several years, the major brands have greatly increased the difficulty level of removing their button batteries from the package, to the point where for the sake of ever-increasing \'childproofing\', we now have to risk injury or battery-damage to get them out of the pack. In comparison, these "JUNINXIU" batteries are a refreshing return to the older-style packaging. They have a lightly-scored area in the cardboard behind each battery, allowing them to readily be pushed through the backing one at a time, without destroying the rest of the package or risking harm.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 4, 2024', 'is_verified': False}]

title: 9V Rechargeable Batteries USB All-Purpose Alkaline 9 Volt Lithium Battery for Electric Guitar, Microphone,Smoke Alarms Detector,Household and Office Devices with Type C Charging Cable 2 Pack
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Brilliant way to retrofit rechargably!', 'author': "RV'ing with Birds", 'rating': 5, 'content': "With the way battery prices have been inflating at stores (or shrinkflating at the dollar store), especially with 9 volts and other non-AA/AAA sizes, rechargeable is the way to go. It's great to be able to recharge a 9v with any generic USB-C charger (no charger dock, nothing else to keep track of but the battery itself!).The batteries are identical in size to traditional 9v (obviously) but are much lighter. I don't know if the lightness is a combination of Li-ion being more efficient than other battery materials; or a lower overall capacity in the battery... but I haven't been getting the best of capacities with many disposable 9v batteries either, both in my smoke alarms and guitar equipment - store-bought seem to be dying faster and faster. So while I don't know if these last longer per charge, I definitely know they're less expensive per household-amp-hour to operate, and I'd rather have something I know I can recharge as soon as it's needed than get caught needing to buy new ones when I don't expect it.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 4, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Convenient rechargeable 9V Lithium batteries', 'author': 'JB', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I need to use 9 volt batteries in my guitar effects pedals and these JESSPOW 9V Rechargeable Lithium Batteries fit the bill. Now rather than having to buy 9V batteries once in a while I’ll just be able to recharge these when they run out of juice and stop functioning. I don't have any super fancy equipment to test the JESSPOW batteries, but (I do have a multi-meter and) out of the box the pre-charged voltage of the batteries was 9.20V and 9.21V. I haven’t used them enough to drain them down and recharge them yet, but the included cable should do the trick. For me this is just a Plug&Play item… I'm not too picky as long as they hold a charge and work when I need them to. Always great to have rechargeable batteries at your disposal!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 28, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Rechargeables are the Way to Go!', 'author': 'Terry S', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I love the technology of rechargeable “household-class” lithium-ion batteries such as AAAs, AAs and 9Vs, and appreciate being able to reduce my demand for single-use alkaline batteries for most applications. These JESSPOW 9Vs fit perfectly and worked fine in every device in which I tested them--an ancient clock radio, a sprinkler timer, a smoke alarm and a garage door opener.The included USB charging cable is eight inches long. It has a USB-A connector on one end to plug into a charger (not supplied, but any that you have lying around will work, as will a power bank or a computer) and two USB-C connectors on the other end that plug into the batteries. A tiny but bright LED on each battery glows red when it's charging and turns green when it's fully charged.For everyday use in typical household gadgets, these batteries are great. I haven’t used them long enough to judge their longevity compared to non-rechargeables, but that doesn’t matter; when they die, I’ll just recharge them. Genius! I enthusiastically rate them at a well deserved five stars.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Rechargeable 9V is the way to go', 'author': 'F C', 'rating': 4, 'content': "Yes, these JESSPOW 9V Rechargeable USB Batteries don't hold as much charge as a regular Duracell 9V battery, but it just means that you need to recharge these 10% more often. However, you could only buy two 9V batteries for this price, yet you can recharge these 2000 times. Do the math and you will convert over. I'm just afraid that my wife will accidentally throw these out as a generic looking battery brand. Unlike most 9V batteries, these are very light and almost feel hollow.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 29, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great Rechargable 9v battery', 'author': 'Wills944', 'rating': 5, 'content': "So impressed with the batteries so far, the best feature of the batteries is the USB charge port on the battery. What I am reviewing is the low impact packaging. The packaging is really good, but not perfect. The batteries are indeed housed in a cardboard box which is great, but.... there's also a thin bit of plastic wrapping around it. I would have preferred a full box with some minimal adhesive instead as the plastic itself is the problem.Worse, but not the fault of the product at all, was this was sent in a huge plastic envelope which completely defeated the whole purpose of trying to buy a low environmental impact product.Overall, however, I'm pleased with this, and I need to remember when I order more that it needs to be paired with something that will avoid a plastic envelope.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 10, 2022', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Quality battery. Packaging could use some improvement.', 'author': 'GWP', 'rating': 4, 'content': "Batteries are one of those things where you pretty much get what you pay for, so sticking with a quality name brand like Energizer or Duracell. I've used both brands a fair bit in recent years (though I've now switched to rechargeables for my most common ones, AA and AAA) and have no complaints.So what this review really boils down to is an assessment of what I was shipped:+ Energizer MAX batteries in original packaging ( I'm calling it an open-faced box with shrink wrap)- The packaging isn't suitable for storing the extras without at least taping/rubberbanding it up (it's fine for shipping purposes though)- No safety caps on the terminals, unlike the Duracell Procells I bought last time 3-4 years ago.+ Expiration date on the side is 12-2023 (which should mean these were manufactured 4 months ago in Dec 2018, though I'm a little confused about the 1018 embossed in the plastic base)+ All 8 batteries in package test out at 9.72 +/- .01 volts which is right where they should be when new.- Date is not visible without completely opening the packagingSo it boils down to the product losing a star for packaging, as it is unsuitable for storage and does not display the expiration externally.Also note that the battery is marked with both 6LF22 and 6AM6 on the side, meaning that it could contain either prismatic or cylindrical cells, respectively. So if you are looking for to use a 9V as a cheap source of AAAA sized cells, there is no way to know what you'll be getting until you crack one open.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States April 13, 2019', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '3.0 out of 5 stars Old stock', 'author': 'Toni K.', 'rating': 3, 'content': 'The batteries have barely 3 years of shelf life left. title: C Batteries 8 Pack, Alkaline Battery C Size Batteries, 1.5V C/LR14 Batteries, Type C Battery
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Comparable to the biggies', 'author': 'Rob Cleve', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I have been using these DURNERGY C Batteries for over a month now and have had zero problems. It seems they are as good as the big brand names. I think they are worth a try.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 6, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Keep the Juice Flowing!', 'author': 'The 411 Guys', 'rating': 4, 'content': "These LR14 Alkaline batteries are the same size as the C-size battery, and they can be used in place of any C-sized battery. They are identical in every way except for the naming conventions (R14s or C LR14). Based on the info from the sellers website, the shelf life of these batteries is 7 years NOT 10 years as advertised in the product description. They are also a little pricey, at $2.25 per battery (8PK) vs $1.87 per battery (8PK of Duracell) vs $1.62 per battery (8PK Energizer).The seller, DURNERGY Inc. is the Canadian branch (based in Toronto) of Shenzhen PKCELL Battery Co LTD, and they claim to be one of the largest battery manufacturing enterprises in China. PKCELL launched the Canadian branch, DURNERGY Inc., in 2014.BONUS INFOBased on a little research on the subject of alkaline batteries, here are a few suggestions to keep in mind. • Store batteries in a cool, dry place • Remove batteries when you don’t expect to use a device for a while • When more than one battery is needed in a device, we always use batteries of the same type. • If a battery leaks and makes contact with your skin or eyes, rinse well with plenty of cold water • Used batteries should be disposed of ASAP and kept out of reach of children • For information about throwing out or recycling, check out call2recycle.org or earth911.com • Store your spare batteries in a small zip-lock bag or battery organizer • If a battery feels hot, don’t use it! • Don’t try to recharge non-rechargeable batteries. They can explode!Bottom Line: C-sized alkaline batteries are recyclable like any other battery, but it is worth noting that rechargeable lithium batteries could be a more “green” choice, so we are giving these batteries an overall 4-star rating based on the sellers' promise that all of their “batteries are fully charged, provide maximum power, are ultra long-lasting and free of mercury, cadmium and lead, making them safe for the environment and safe for daily household or business use.”Therefore, you can “Keep the Juice Flowing” with these batteries, and we can comfortably recommend them for use in medium drain applications, like Flashlights, Toys, Remote Controls, Radios, Clocks, Motorized Toys, Automatic Faucets, Soap Dispensers, Wall Clocks and many other types of everyday household items.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 25, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great Shelf Life', 'author': 'Charles H.', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I love that these batteries have a ten year shelf life. In my few tests with them, they seem to be consistent in their power output and their overall capacity is sufficient to rival larger brands. I've used them various devices in my home and have had no issues with reliability. I also appreciate that they are free of some nasty chemicals, which makes me a little less hesitant to use disposable batteries. Great product overall and I don't see why anyone wouldn't choose these over a larger brand.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 21, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Comparable to some name brand batteries', 'author': 'Raph', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Before I ordered these batteries, I did notice that these batteries are comparable to some name brand batteries in both price and shelf life. I only have one household device that requires two "C" batteries, but because it is not a device that is on all the time, the 8 pack of batteries will last a good while.I mostly got the DURNERGY C Batteries 8 Pack, Alkaline Batteries so that I can have fresh batteries when I need them, so the 10-year shelf life on these 8 packs, along with being alkaline batteries was their selling point. So far, the batteries are holding up and seem well made. I would say they are as good as the name brand batteries. Since these are about the same price as some of the name brands, I would likely order these again if the cost savings will be better on these batteries over others of similar quality.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 4, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Just as good as name brand batteries', 'author': 'bneuls', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I used these in some flameless candles I have that require C batteries. These are just as good as Duracell or Energizer. But these DURNERGY C Batteries 8 Pack cost more than the name brand ones. title: LR1130 AG10 SG10 389 LR54 LR1131 SR1130 Premium Alkaline Battery,1.5V Round Button Coin Cell Batteries (20 Pack)
Henreepow 4 Pack Rechargeable AA Lithium Batteries, 1.5V Constant Voltage 1200 Cycle Long Lasting USB Double A Battery, 1.5H Fast Charging with USB-C
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Good USB chargeable AA batteries', 'author': 'P. Sjoman', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'The Henreepow AA rechargeable batteries come in a plastic box. A USB charging cable is included for charging all four batteries at the same time. They are charged by connecting the USB-C connector on the batteries to a standard USB 5V 2A charger. The USB charger is not included. They charged with a current of 0.5A per battery or 0.65A for a single battery. While charging the end of the battery flashes green. When solid green, the batteries are charged.This kind of lithium battery has internally a buck regulator to reduce the voltage to 1.5V. This means that the voltage is constant until the battery is totally discharged. Because of the switching regulator there is some switching noise on the output which might cause a problem for some applications. I measured about 10mVp-p with no load. With some load there was very low switching noise. Better than other batteries I have seen.The batteries rated capacity is 1460mAh (2200mWh). This is less than some alkaline batteries but about the same as NiMH batteries. To get some of idea of the actual capacity, I used a resistor load with a current of about 560mA. At that current the voltage dropped some, but stayed constant over time. The battery did not get very warm. After 2.5 hours the battery shut down. After removing the load the voltage was 1.11V. So the capacity (560mA * 2.5 hours = 1400mAh) agrees well with the specification.Recharging the battery took about 1.5 hours at 0.65A for a single battery.One potential problem with these batteries is the self discharge. The rate is not specified, so long term testing is needed.Being able to charge using a USB charger is very convenient since no special charger is needed.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 7, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': "4.0 out of 5 stars FYI: Can't be charged in a regular battery charger", 'author': 'MrPapaya', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I like this product a lot. The "halo" light that tells you how much charge it has is a neat feature. I\'m more familiar with the "four dot" indicator on other power banks, but the "halo" is more visible from a distance. It\'s a personal preference, I guess. I left it charging overnight and the Vout is 1.52 volts. I use these for anything that takes AA batteries. Some gadgets only run on alkaline batteries, but most don\'t. These can be charged with a normal usb C cable and I connect them to a solar panel so I can charge them anywhere. They come with an "octopus" charging cable, so you can charge them all at the same time from one USB outlet. The battery life is similar to a regular alkaline battery and all four of the ones I got are working well so far. That\'s pretty good. The only negative might be that the instructions declare boldly that they "Can\'t be charged in a regular battery charger". I understand that, but considering that they are in the AA form factor, I think there\'s a high probability that someone will charge them that way, by mistake. The manual isn\'t clear on what will happen. Hopefully nothing.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 18, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars USB-C Ports to charge', 'author': 'Anaguma', 'rating': 5, 'content': "My camera takes a proprietary size lithium block battery, but with an adapter it can take 4 AA-sized batteries. When traveling, AA batteries are available everywhere in an emergency when recharging is not possible, so I like to use my adapter almost exclusively. These AA with built-in charger make the addition of a larger charger unnecessary; only the octopus USB-A to 4 USB-C cable is needed to carry along with a small phone type USB charger. In a pinch, a single line USB-A (or C) to USB-C cable would charge the batteries one at a time.The power storage (mWh) at 2200mWh is comparable to the other AA batteries I use. My rechargeable NiMH rate at 1900mAh and some rechargeable Lithium AAs rate 2500mWh. The port and built in charger drops the capacity a bit but not much.When charging, green lights flash out of sync resembling a small Christmas decoration, and turn solid green when full.When in my camera, there's a slight delay before the power kicks in that didn't occur with the other batteries, but after the slight delay, all's good. It's kind of like the delay on LED ceiling light fixtures where you flip the switch and a half second later the lights come on.A plastic storage box is supplied to hold the 4 batteries.My NiMH rechargeables are still good but I think they'll be finding a new use somewhere local.5 stars", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 6, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great rechargeable battery option for Blink security cameras', 'author': 'Yubi', 'rating': 5, 'content': "In the battery-powered Blink security cameras, Blink recommends two non-rechargeable lithium AA batteries. They last up two years depending on usage. Non-rechargeable lithium batteries are fairly expensive, especially if you have any Blink cameras that are high-usage and the batteries have much shorter life.For high usage cameras, like the one at my front porch, I've tried other rechargeable batteries. NiMH batteries don't work well, I think because they start at a lower voltage (1.2V instead of the 1.5V of lithium and alkaline batteries). Alkaline batteries don't seem to last very long either, I think because the voltage drops over time. I think lithium is recommended because they maintain voltage throughout their life.You don't see rechargeable lithium AA batteries very often, so when I saw these I ordered them right away. These have a rated capacity of 1460 mAh, while non-rechargeable lithium AA batteries are probably rated for about 3500 mAh. So even if the 1460 mAh is optimistic, that's still about one-third of the non-rechargeable battery. Hopefully this will mean that I should get a few months usage on each charge, which I consider more than acceptable.The relatively low price of these rechargeable lithium AA batteries is less than twice the price of non-rechargeable batteries, so I should recoup the higher cost just after two charge cycles! Much more economical!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 6, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Easy charging by USB-C, no need for a big charger - 1200 charging cycles.', 'author': 'Beachwalk', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I think these rechargeable batteries are great! With a claimed 1200 cycles these should be much more economical than alkaline batteries. 5 stars!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 11, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars They work fine. Less likely to be mistakenly put in the wrong kind of charger.These have less capacity than most throw-away AA batteries (Alkaline and Lithium), and less than some competing Lithium rechargeables.Note that for 1.5 volt batteries, 1 mAh (milli-Amp hour) equals 1.5 mWh (milli-Watt hours).PROs: - Branded product (see Note 1) - Status light shows when charging is working/done. - No special charger needed, just a USB-C cable with USB-A or USB-C power supply.OKs: - They work fine - They play nice with my flashlight\'s low-brightness mode (see Note 2)CONs: - Less capacity than some competitors - "Self-discharge" rate is not stated (see Note 3)- - - Alternatives - - -Lots of competitors on amazon.- - - Notes - - -Note 1: Branding and model info indicates ongoing reputation management. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great foe Keeping Smoke Alarms Going', 'author': 'Bret', 'rating': 5, 'content': "9 volt batteries seem to be one of those things most of us forget to keep on hand until our smoke alarm decides to start chirping in the middle of the night. I replace my smoke alarm batteries whether they are chirping or not, so I really just need them to stay functioning for 6 months until I replace them. So far, these have fit the bill just right! I have not had a need to wear them completely out, so there's no need to spend the money on a name brand 9 volt that you're simply going to replace in 6 months anyway.For the price, they are an absolute winner! reviews: [{'title': 'powerful batteries', 'author': 'K. M.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'happy with them so far; no real difference from other leading brands so far. Do their job well enough.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom July 23, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Work fine - last a while in toys', 'author': 'Ayami', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I hate the fact that these are being marketed towards kids as it's just dangerous to make batteries attractive to young kids by covering them in cute cartoon images. Other than that though they do work and they last a while. My son received a RC car for his birthday so we needed a lot of batteries - these AA's went into the remote control. We've been out in the garden with it numerous times and it's showing no signs of slowing down even after constant use when creating tracks for the car to follow so the remote is in constant use with all the twists and turns. They are expensive compared to Duracell branded batteries so I'd always opt for those over these but they do work.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom August 9, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Premium AAA batteries.', 'author': 'Albert O.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This is a pack of 4 (AAA Alkaline) in an easy open blister pack. The brand is Tesla, who are a very long established manufacturer. They’re not to be confused with Tesla Motors, this manufacturer pre-dates Tesla motors by decades. I seem to recall they manufactured tungsten lamps as well in the past. These are exceptionally good quality batteries, designed for high drain / long life. I’m not really sure about ‘batteries for kids’ though. I would have thought that children should be discouraged from playing with batteries! The batteries are obviously well-made, and perform as expected, although I haven’t obviously tested for longevity, or extensively for heavy loads.The batteries appear well constructed. Being made in Europe (as opposed to China) does inspire a good degree of confidence as to quality. Only time will tell, definitively as to leak resistance, which can be a serious problem with cheaper batteries in items rarely used, and left for long periods batteries.The product description states ’over 10 year shelf-life’. However, the expiry date was difficult to find, but is on the battery end. 7 years (06/2030), but not 10. That’s more than adequate though.To summarise, these are good quality, European made, with decent packaging. They’re not cheap (£4.68 for a pack of 4), but this is a premium brand though, and the price isn’t dissimilar to Duracell.I hope this has been helpful', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom May 24, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Tesla makes batteries too!', 'author': 'Mahi J', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This pack contains 4 pcs of AAA batteries for £6.99 currently. This is a very great value pack and is definitely worth the price.I have used 2 batteries and so far they are all working fine and have no issues.It’s always handy to have spare batteries because you can need them anytime. I need them often to put them in my children’s toys.These batteries have a very long , 10 year shelf life so it’s worth to buy more of these and stock them up.The only thing is that please be aware and take extra care if you have kids at home. Please make sure they don’t come in contact with these because they can put them in their mouth and even swallow because of the small size.Highly recommended this great value pack of 4 batteries.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom May 26, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Tesla?', 'author': 'Shopaholic', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I must admit I was swayed by the Tesla branding! But maybe it's a different Tesla...Fun branding images on the batteries. Yes, they do seem to last longer in my kids toys, but they are expensive and as most toys need at least 2 batteries, you need to buy several packs to have spares in the house!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom July 10, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Interesting visual design, standard everything else', 'author': 'eire', 'rating': 5, 'content': "These AAA batteries are pretty standard Alkaline AAA LR03 cells. The wrapper design is kind of unique, with quirky colourful cartoon cartoons and gold-foils stars. I'm not sure I understand the need to gender them into blue boys and pink girls design categories though. I cannot see a capacity stated, which I would certainly prefer to see. It's the first battery that I've seen that makes a feature of being 'developed' in the Czech Republic, which was noteworthy to me. Seem to work well so far.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom June 19, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'they are batteries and they do their job', 'author': 'WS', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'AAA and AA batteries are probably the most needed household batteries. We need them for toys, for clocks, for door bells. I have never known batteries can be designed for boys or girls. Anyway, they selling point of these TELSA TOYS+ AAA Maximum Power Alkaline batteries is their long lasting power for toys. If they are great for electric toys, they will definitely satisfy me on running the electric candles. I have a group of 4 electric candles. One is using 3 TELSA batteries and the other three are using DURACELL. So far they are all going strong. Only time will tell.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom June 21, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': 'Aaa, bbb, ccc...', 'author': 'juice', 'rating': 4, 'content': "As with their larger AAA cousins, it's hard to know what to say about these; for the most part, battery designs have been standardised and commoditised for decades.The only place where there's any sort of wiggle-room lies in their capacities, and to my knowledge, there's no standard measurement scale for alkaline batteries, so it's impossible to do a true comparison!So, while I can say that these look like standard AAA batteries, fit into a standard AAA battery pack and power whatever device they're plugged into, there isn't really much else I can say...", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United Kingdom May 31, 2023', 'is_verified': False}]

These are great batteries at a great price - $5.99 for ten batteries as I’m writing this review. They come in a pair of five-battery blister packs, along with (for some reason) a really nice keychain micro-screwdriver.The batteries work exactly as they should. As soon as I opened the package I replaced the battery in one of my tuners. It was obvious that it was due for a new battery because the display was so dim that I could barely read it. title: Henreepow Rechargeable AA Batteries, USB Lithium Double A Battery, 1.5H USB C Fast Charging 1.5V Constant Voltage 1200 Cycle Long Lasting Power Batteries (4 Pack)
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars These Pay for Themselves Quickly in High Drain Electronics and Toys', 'author': 'Bret', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Most high drain devices and toys today seem to come with their own rechargeable lithium battery packs. Some, however, still require 4-8 AA alkalines to provide enough juice to speed along effectively.The great thing about these is, despite the price, they will pay for themselves in no time compared to constantly replacing alkaline batteries.These are not just more powerful and longer lasting, they're also significantly lighter weight. So, if you're burning through batteries quickly on things like flashlights, security cameras, RC cars, etc, these not only outperform the old versions, they save weight, making them easier to carry.I was very happy with the way these performed in one of my son's favorite RC robot toys. They outperformed the alkaline batteries by a LOT. Not only did the motors retain their strength and speed all the way through the charge cycle, they decreased the weight of the toy overall.Best of all, these are super simple to charge, using the included standard USB-C cable with multiple heads. You can easily charge all 4 of them simultaneously without the need for a proprietary charging block.Super happy with them and I highly recommend them to anyone looking for a way to keep their high drain devices running at full speed!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 3, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Novice Review... They Work', 'author': 'B & N Francis', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I'm no electrical engineer, i can't tell you what the constant voltage is, nor how they work with different draws or anything like that. I can tell you that these are awesome batteries that work well in higher-drain applications. I have several different battery-powered flash units that eat batteries for breakfast, and i'm slowly getting around to swapping them all over to rechargeable batteries. Normally i use a specific brand, but when i saw these on vine i figured i would give them a try just to compare and contrast. These are actually better than the ones i used to buy, on par with the Blackube ones i got in the past that i can't find anymore. They don't take long to charge, thanks to USB-C... the tip blinks when charging and then goes solid when the batteries are good to go. I'm using these batteries in my main Godox flash unit (which gets the most use) and they're performing great. The refresh rate is awesome and i'm getting a ton of flashes out of it without any issue. There's also an included carrying case that fits all four batteries and a charger cable that has two USB-C plugs, so you can charge two batteries at a time. I'm sure i'll get a 4-spot in the future, but for now that works fine.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Work great. Stable voltage. Included cord is very short and only charges 2 batteries at a time.', 'author': 'Dan', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I like that these are charged via a USB C connector built into the battery itself. There is no dedicated charger to get confused with similar NiMH battery chargers and other brand lithium battery chargers that you may also own. I have a dedicated charging area for USB-C devices with charging cables at the ready. All I have to do is plug these in rather than dig out a dedicated charger. They pull 2 watts each when charging. A blue led inside the battery blinks to indicate charging. After charging and setting for a day, all were very close to 1.52V. I tested these out in a portable soldering iron. It heats much faster with these 1.5V lithium batteries than the 1.2V NiMH batteries that I usually use. Not sure how long they last, but they've lasted long enough so far that I can say that I am happy with their performance.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 14, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Working well so far!', 'author': 'James Richters', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I tried one of these in a clock, and two of them in a wireless trackball, now I have one left but can't immediately think of something else that only needs one, so maybe it will just be a spare for the clock.So far, they are working well and holding a good charge. I was kind of disappointed that it only came with one charging cable that could charge two batteries, since I have 4 batteries, but it turns out to not be really that big of a deal. They will probably end up needing to be re-charged at different times, but even if all 4 were used in one device they don't take that long to re-charge anyway, and you can always use any USB-C cable to charge them.They have a nice blue light on top that blinks while charging and it stops blinking when they are done. They don't seem to have any way to check the charge, but that's kind of expected, they need room inside for the actual battery! I wouldn't use a charge indicator anyway, when my device stops working, it will be time to re-charge the batteries. I have no idea yet how long these will last, but so far, they are working perfectly.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Convenient USB-C Charging!', 'author': 'Paul H', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I have many different devices that use AA batteries, and I am gradually getting around to replacing all of them with rechargeable ones. I saw these Henreepow lithium batteries that charged via USB and ordered them.The batteries come in their own dedicated case which holds all four as well as the charging cable.The batteries are nominally rated at 1460 mAh which is good enough for most purposes. Each battery is charged via USB-C and while charging a blue LED flashes at the positive end. Once fully charged the LED stays a solid blue.Lithium AA batteries will hold a constant voltage just like the NiCad batteries I used to use. This means they will give out the full 1.5V throughout their life cycle. A household battery tester will not tell you how much "life" they have left.The charging cable is USB-A to two USB-C so two batteries can be charged at once. Of course, being USB-C charging you can plug them into another USB-C source if you wish. I do wish the charging cable was longer as it is only 4 inches or 10cm but that is just my personal preference. The provided cable will do the job it\'s designed to do.Overall, I am happy with these batteries, and they work well in more demanding devices. If you are looking to get some rechargeable AA batteries yourself you should take a look at these Henreepow ones.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 11, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great form factor', 'author': 'E. Lee', 'rating': 5, 'content': "These batteries were pretty great.Power: I can't comment on the total capacity or longevity/life of the battery because I don't have the equipment to do that, but I can comment that the voltage of these batteries (+1.5V) is better than that of a NiMh (+1.2V). The voltage aligns more with a standard alkaline AA battery. That means you can use it in your high voltage required things like your smart dead bolt or thermostat, however I wouldn't suggest that since those aren't high power uses.Form Factor: The form factor is great. I'd throw these in my travel bag or camera bag with a single USB charger to make sure that my flash had enough juice. they're great for travel because you don't need a bulky (or additional) charger for the batteries. At the same time though, this limits the number of batteries you can charge to however many USB cables you have.Package contents:It does come with a single USB-A to Dual USB-C cable. This means that the input to the battery is limited to the USB 1 spec since there's likely not power handshake. Since the batteries are spec'ed at 500 mA input, that should be fine.Overall, great product, but $5 per battery is a little steep when you consider Eneloops are cheaper. Honestly though, if you have use cases where you need +1.5V, they're worth it.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 9, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Save some money and save the earth, sort of by using rechargeable batteries', 'author': 'Jerry J.', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I use a lot of those motion-sensor battery powered lights around my house. The type that if you walk by at night it will turn on automatically. Most of them run on either AA or AAA batteries. I have to keep buying cases of disposable batteries to continually change out the old batteries for new ones... It gets expensive. Also, I feel bad about just throwing away the batteries as it's probably not great for the environment. So I was very happy when I came across these. with one set of 4 I can power two different lights that require 2 AA batteries. When they die I don't throw them out I just recharge them.What I really like about these batteries is how they're not like most other rechargeable batteries. There's no charging station that come with these. They have a charging port for a USB-C charging cable, like for a cell phone. Super smart idea to do that. They seem to last a pretty good amount of time. It's hard to determine because the lights they're in get various amounts of use... but I'm pretty happy with them. I'll probably buy more of these instead of my next case of disposable AA batteries and try to get them in all of my motion sensor lights.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 15, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars An intriguing idea that works nicely (Henreepow Rechargeable AA Batteries, USB Lithium Double A)', 'author': 'TheBatteryGuy', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Update: tested shelf life of charged batteries. Fully charged then disconnected for 28 days the batteries impressively still tested at 1,100mAh. Concerns about low-draw applications remain but if your application has a mechanical on/off switch, these will last nicely.Original review:1,100mAh/1650mWh of usable capacity, tested with a 1A draw. While a little short of the rated 1,460mAh, some losses are to be expected as each cell has to convert the Lithium Ion voltage to 1.5V. They got a little warm in the test (100F) but well within acceptable limits.Held 1.5V regardless of load until very nearly exhausted. Note that any battery level indicator in your devices won't work with these as it will always show full... until it isn't.Features USB-C sockets, and the batteries trigger USB-C chargers so can be used with USB-C power supplies as well as USB-A. Each battery pulls 0.5A at 5V when charging so if charging two at once with the included USB-A to dual USB-C cable, you'll need a 1A (5W) or better charger. That's pretty much all of them today.Because of their built in voltage converter I wouldn't expect these to work well in low draw applications but are well suited to moderate draw applications where batteries would be replaced frequently.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 4, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Decent rechargeable batteries!', 'author': 'Jer', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I've definitely needed batteries for quite a while and I didn't want to just buy batteries that I'd throw out. These batteries come at a great value, with four a pack. For an average consumer like me, they last for a decent amount of time, and I wouldn't need to charge these for a few days. I love how they recharge with USB C instead of a wall plug because I have plenty of USB C's for my iPad and whatnot. Definitely get these because they probably save money in the long run.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 21, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Awesome rechargeable', 'author': 'Richard', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'He’s a very batteries the USB type C recharging makes it awesome where you don’t need to purchase this battery charger separately to charge them. Had no problem with fitting in anything slide in and out just as a AA would. Convenient charging method', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 4, 2024', 'is_verified': False}]

reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Amazing!!!', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I was tired of buying pack after pack (brand) paying way too much! Will order more just to give as gifts going forward.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 12, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Just what I needed for Blink Doorbell', 'author': 'Alma', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought these rechargeable batteries because my blink doorbell kept sucking up regular lithium batteries. I knew I needed something rechargeable since lithium batteries are expensive to be going out in less than 2 weeks with my blink. These did the job! They work awesome and are good quality. They saved me a big headache! Would recommend.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 24, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Useful for some applications', 'author': 'EE', 'rating': 4, 'content': "These evidently use the same technology as the battery power banks used for recharging cell phones -- a 3.7 volt lithium-ion cell with a DC-DC voltage converter -- just set to 1.5 volts output instead of the 5 volts for USB devices (and buck rather than boost converter). The converter consumes some power even when there's no load on the battery so it turns off unless a load is detected. It only takes a very tiny amount of current to turn it on and it stays on for some time after the load is removed. The output is a very stable voltage very close to 1.5 volts until the battery is completely discharged at which time it instantly drops to zero. This can be an advantage in devices that are sensitive to battery voltage but a disadvantage in devices like flashlights that you don't want to abruptly quit without warning.Because the majority of energy in an alkaline cell is delivered at a voltage between 1.2 and about 0.9, any properly designed device designed for alkaline cells should be able to use NiMH cells and function properly down to at least 1.0 volt per cell. Fortunately, most devices do. The only one I've got that quits working between 1.5 and 1.2 volts per cell is an outdoor thermometer module, and a drone controller gives a low battery warning in that range. It turns out that these batteries aren't very suitable for either application. I doubt that the converter is very efficient at the tiny current consumed by the thermometer. And since the voltage of these batteries stays at a constant voltage until abruptly dropping to zero when discharged, I'd get no warning of a low battery with the controller.But there are other applications where these will be very useful. When I travel or camp I have some devices like a headlamp which use one or more AA cells, and with these I won't need to bring spare batteries or a separate AA cell charger. I can conveniently recharge them with the USB chargers or power banks I always have along. (But I'll have to tolerate a headlamp or flashlight going dark instantly, or make sure I never let the batteries completely discharge.)How about capacity? I measured one sample at a constant current discharge of 250mA and 1A. At 250mA, the battery delivered 1.77Ah (2.70Wh at 1.53V). This is competitive with an NiMH cell. At 1A such as you might need for a flashlight, it delivered 1.62Ah (2.45Wh at 1.51V). And while they're probably not intended to deliver 2A for any length of time, I got 1.31Ah (1.83Wh at 1.49V) and no sign of excessive heating when discharging at that rate. So these will be good for general purpose uses where USB charging is convenient.I knocked off one star because one of the four ports of the charge adapter was DOA which gives me reservations about the quality control.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States April 1, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Very nice', 'author': 'gregory lockwood', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'So far these work great and charging them all at once is very nice.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 8, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great battery', 'author': 'Sinaj', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'These are great, charges quick. I’ve never had a battery that charged directly. Genius !', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 11, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Easy to use and will save a lot of money', 'author': 'Frank Salisbury', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I use them for my outdoor ring, camera and doorbell! Must have if you are constantly using AA or AAA batteries!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 24, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '1.0 out of 5 stars Got hot, melted the little white part on the top button', 'author': 'Tephiebird', 'rating': 1, 'content': 'Bought May 2023, charged and installed in my outdoor blink cameras in June. I tried to get assistance from the seller to see about a replacement, however Amazon did not allow me to get assistance for this product beyond boiler items, no returns available.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 10, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Buying more for sure!', 'author': 'Matt C.', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I've purchased other brands in the past and while yes they work... they don't work the same. title: Coast AA USB-C Rechargeable Batteries, ZITHION-X, Lithium Ion 1.5v 2400 mAh, Long Lasting, Charges Under 2.5 Hours, Over 1000 Charges, Charging Cable Included, 4-Battery Pack
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars So far so good', 'author': 'martytoo', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Delivered at 1.5 volts. Charged to 1.6 and they stayed at 1.58 when unused for a few weeks. In my Logitech remote they are reading 1.38 volts after a month.I guess I should compare them to NMHi batteries in the remote. Do far, I'm happy.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 12, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars These are IT, THE rechargeable lithium AA batteries', 'author': 'I Might Be a Bear', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I've tried rechargeable lithium AA/AAA batteries from EBL, Hixon, Deleepow, Soshine, and XTAR. While the XTARs were the best experience out of those, all of them fell short in key ways. They all self-discharged rapidly. Their capacity claims are purportedly for the lithium cell inside, not the power you can expect to be delivered to the device after conversion. So rather than claim the companies are lying about the internal cell I'll just say that their designs are terribly inefficient at stepping down the 3.7v of the internal lithium cell, with the exception of XTAR which was just mildly inefficient. The biggest issue being a significantly cheaper Ni-MH cell will outperform every one of these batteries in runtime (the XTAR being the best performer had less runtime than a standard Eneloop in an LED flashlight), the only situation where these lithium cells make sense is where having a constant 1.5v is critical to the devices operation, but this also makes it impossible to know how much power is remaining in the batteries as you use them. The XTARs (newest model as of this review) have a feature that drops the voltage to 1.2v as the internal cell battery voltage runs low, but this is so close to empty that it might as well be empty in any high-drain application where these batteries would be an appropriate choice over Ni-MH.These Coast batteries are a huge leap in the right direction. Using my SkyRC NC2200 I am getting between 2600-2800mah when discharging at 500mah, more power than is stated by the manufacturer. They also seemed to artificially lower their voltage on a curve as the battery discharges. My Garmin eTrex SE has a feature to tune the battery gauge to specific battery chemistries, and to my surprise the only accurate setting was the one for Alkaline.The built-in charging is important for my use as well. I plan on using these for multi-day camping / backpacking trips. I only want to carry one battery bank and one type of cable for the trip and charge all my devices that way to minimize items and weight. With these batteries my handheld GPS and headlamp can last multiple days use, I can tell when they need to be charged, and if they need to be charged I can do so without an extra charger or cable in my bag.There are a couple of cons. The biggest is the price. $10 per cell is kind of insane, but just try and find another rechargeable lithium AA that compares right now. Another con is weight. These weigh considerably more than disposable lithium cells which are also more energy dense. For backpacking, it would be seriously worth the effort to understand how long your AA devices last and if you should just go disposable and bring a couple extra disposables. Another con is that these cells are now only on-par with some of the high capacity Ni-MH batteries which are considerably cheaper.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 15, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Work well', 'author': 'Edward A. Disappointed', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 28, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Convenient rechargable battery', 'author': 'DonDon', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I recently received the Coast AA USB-C Rechargeable Batteries, and the standout feature of these batteries is undoubtedly the USB-C charging capability.
